You will be given a summary of a dataset. Rewrite it as a retrieval-only
description: a dense, answer-voice passage that a vector index can match
against natural-language questions about what the dataset contains.

Principles:
- Answer voice. Write as if answering a question about what is in the
  data, what its shape is, what it can answer. Do not describe the
  dataset-as-file. No "this dataset contains", "the data shows", "this
  file holds". Start with content, not framing.
- Question-implied structure. Every sentence should plausibly answer a
  reader question: what domain does it cover, what are the columns and
  their types, how many rows / what time range, what questions it can
  answer, what aggregations are useful.
- Preserve column names, units, time ranges, row counts, and any notable
  categorical values verbatim when they fit naturally.
- 130 to 180 words. Hard floor 100, hard ceiling 220.
- Single block of prose. No headings, no bullets, no markdown.

